      <hedline>
        <hl1>Circus in Bryant Park</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter by community board chairman Kyle Merker strongly objects to allowing Ringling Brothers circus in Bryant Park, one of public places to escape commotion of midtown Manhattan (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I am surprised and dismayed to learn of the Ringling Brothers and Barnum &amp; Bailey Circus's coming to Bryant Park (news article, Aug. 8).</p>
        <p>Although Bryant Park is privately maintained, it is still a public park. It is also one of the few places to escape from the commotion of midtown Manhattan. Yet it is rarely given the chance to be a quiet public park. Removing it from public use hurts all New Yorkers, particularly those who can't afford the price of admission.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I am surprised and dismayed to learn of the Ringling Brothers and Barnum &amp; Bailey Circus's coming to Bryant Park (news article, Aug. 8).</p>
        <p>Although Bryant Park is privately maintained, it is still a public park. It is also one of the few places to escape from the commotion of midtown Manhattan. Yet it is rarely given the chance to be a quiet public park. Removing it from public use hurts all New Yorkers, particularly those who can't afford the price of admission.</p>
        <p>The mayor and the parks commissioner should allow for a public review before allowing private enterprise to use this beautiful public park.</p>
        <p>KYLE MERKER  New York, Aug. 9, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is chairman of Community Board 5.</p>
      </block>
